# A racy program much larger than "Hello World!", for exercising the HPC
# (distributed) verifier: a shared global `value` is stored, loaded, and proven
# `== 0` repeatedly. Each racy load/store is an interleaving point, so under the
# 2-hart system the verifier explores a tree of hundreds of thousands of
# continuations - a search worth distributing across a cluster.
#
# `global` locality makes the loads/stores racy (they would otherwise default to
# thread-local); the inferred word-sized accesses fix `value: u32`.
value: global _
t0 = &value
t2 = 0

# Block 1: racy store, racy load, proof obligation `value == 0`.
t0[0:4] = t2
t1 = t0[0:4]
require t1 == t2

# Block 2.
t0[0:4] = t2
t1 = t0[0:4]
require t1 == t2

# Block 3.
t0[0:4] = t2
t1 = t0[0:4]
require t1 == t2

# Block 4.
t0[0:4] = t2
t1 = t0[0:4]
require t1 == t2

# A final racy load + obligation (an odd number of racy accesses widens the
# interleaving tree further).
t1 = t0[0:4]
require t1 == t2

unreachable
